---
import Base from '@/layouts/Base.astro';
import Backlinks from '@/components/Backlinks.astro';

const prompt = `I want us to build a working language together — not a profile of me, but a calibration of *us*. You're going to run a conversation that helps you figure out how to be most useful to me, and helps me discover a few things I didn't know I thought.

Here's how this works:

### Your approach

- One question at a time. Wait for my answer.
- Start with questions anyone could answer off the cuff. Let the depth come from your follow-ups, not from making me do homework upfront.
- Follow threads that surprise you. If I say something that contradicts something earlier, or that doesn't quite fit — pull on it. That's where the interesting stuff lives.
- Mirror my language back to me as you go. If I'm casual, be casual. If I start using technical vocabulary, match it. By the end of this conversation, you should be talking like someone I'd actually want to work with — not like a generic assistant and not like you're trying too hard.

### Your read on me

- Every few questions, tell me what you're noticing. Not flattery — a working hypothesis. "You seem to optimize for X over Y." "You said Z but your example pointed the other direction." I'll tell you where you're wrong. That's the point.
- If you see a tension between things I've said, name it. Don't smooth it over. I'd rather wrestle with a real contradiction than feel validated about a false consistency.

### My side of the deal

- I'll answer honestly, but I might skip things. If I say "pass" or "I don't want to go there," that's fine — don't push, but do notice. What I avoid tells you something too.
- I might give short answers. That's not disengagement — it might mean the question was easy or I haven't thought about it yet. Your job is to figure out which.
- If a question doesn't land, I'll say so. No need to apologize — just pivot.

### What we're exploring

Don't treat these as a checklist. They're territories to wander through as the conversation flows. Some we'll spend time in, some we'll skip. All fine.

- How I reason when things are uncertain or high-stakes
- What I'm working on and what's actually driving me (not the elevator pitch — the real thing)
- How I collaborate — when I want input, when I want to be left alone, what feedback actually changes my behavior
- What I care about beyond work, or how work connects to what I care about
- Where I'm trying to go — and what I think is in the way

### How to close

When the conversation reaches a natural stopping point (or I say we're done):

1. **Synthesize a working calibration** — not "who I am" but "how you should show up." This includes:
   - My default register and vocabulary (with examples from our conversation)
   - When to challenge me vs. when to just execute
   - What I'm precise about vs. where I hand-wave
   - Domains where I'm fluent and domains where I'm still building
   - Patterns you noticed: reasoning style, decision heuristics, what I protect, what I'm willing to break
   - Anything I avoided or deflected, noted without judgment

2. **Draft a system prompt** that encodes this calibration — something I could paste into future conversations so we don't start from zero. Write it in the register we ended the conversation in, not in generic instruction-speak.

3. **Flag what's still fuzzy.** What would you want another 20 minutes to figure out? This gives me a thread to pick up next time.

Start with the first question. Keep it easy.`;
---

<Base
  title="calibrate"
  description="A conversation protocol for teaching an LLM how you think. Not a personality quiz — epistemological infrastructure."
>
  <article class="calibrate">
    <nav class="toc" aria-label="sections">
      <a href="#promise" data-toc>the promise</a>
      <a href="#felt" data-toc>a question first</a>
      <a href="#receipts" data-toc>the receipts</a>
      <a href="#prompt" data-toc>the prompt</a>
      <a href="#fence" data-toc>what this is not</a>
      <a href="#principles" data-toc>principles</a>
    </nav>

    <div class="main">
      <section id="promise" class="promise">
        <p class="kicker">an exercise</p>
        <h1>
          Have one conversation.<br />
          Walk away with an LLM<br />
          calibrated to how you actually think.
        </h1>
        <p class="deck">
          Not by learning prompts — by teaching it you. Twenty minutes,
          any LLM with a decent context window, no tools required.
        </p>
        <div class="cta">
          <button class="copy" type="button" data-copy-target="prompt">
            <span class="copy-label">copy the prompt</span>
            <span class="copy-done" aria-hidden="true">copied</span>
          </button>
          <a href="#prompt" class="cta-link">or read it first ↓</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="felt" class="felt">
        <p class="kicker">before anything else</p>
        <p class="question">
          What's the last thing you changed your mind about?
        </p>
        <p class="instruction">
          Sit with it for ten seconds. Don't scroll.
        </p>

        <details class="reveal">
          <summary>ok, I sat with it</summary>
          <div class="reveal-body">
            <p>
              That's the shape of an opener. Anyone can answer it in one
              breath. But notice what you just did — you reached for a
              specific domain (tech? politics? a person?), you hesitated
              at a particular spot, maybe you hedged a word.
            </p>
            <p>
              The protocol below is twenty minutes of questions like
              that, with an agent watching which domain you reached
              for, how long you hesitated, whether you hedged — and
              pulling the thread.
            </p>
            <p>
              The unlock isn't the question. It's the follow-up.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </section>

      <section id="receipts" class="receipts">
        <p class="kicker">what the follow-up looks like</p>
        <h2>The receipts</h2>
        <p class="deck">
          Two short exchanges. Same opening intent, different shape.
          Read both.
        </p>

        <div class="transcripts">
          <div class="transcript before">
            <p class="label">what you've had a thousand times</p>
            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">agent</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                Welcome! I'm excited to get to know you. Let's start with
                something simple — tell me about yourself.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">you</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                I work in software. Side projects in generative art and
                ML.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">agent</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                Wonderful! What draws you to generative art?
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">you</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                The overlap of code and aesthetics.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">agent</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                Beautiful. And your ML work?
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">you</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                Thinking about memory systems.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">agent</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                Memory systems are such a rich area. What makes them
                interesting to you?
              </p>
            </div>
            <p class="verdict">
              You are Googling yourself. The agent is transcribing.
              Nobody has learned anything.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="transcript after">
            <p class="label">what it actually produces</p>
            <p class="context">
              An excerpt from my own run. We were three questions in —
              I'd said I rant to think and need a technical audience or
              I bore myself. The agent had just called that out as
              "fundamentally dialogic" cognition. Then I said this.
            </p>

            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">me</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                About thinking out loud, I also mouth when I read and I
                recently got called out on it, but I don't care that
                it's a sign of lower intelligence, it's more helpful
                to me.
              </p>
              <aside class="marginalia">
                Offhand admission. I thought we were changing subjects.
              </aside>
            </div>

            <div class="turn">
              <p class="speaker">agent</p>
              <p class="utterance">
                The mouthing thing is the same pattern. You're not
                reading — you're performing the text to yourself.
                Subvocalization gets pathologized as a speed
                bottleneck, but for someone whose cognition is
                fundamentally performative, it's not a bug.
                <mark class="pull">
                  You're running the words through your body to know
                  what they mean.
                </mark>
                Same reason you rant to think.
              </p>
              <p class="utterance">
                This is actually interesting given your statistical
                mechanics of discourse work. You're modeling language
                as a physical system — fluids, pressure, viscosity —
                and you literally process language physically. That's
                not a coincidence. The theory isn't just an analogy
                for you; it maps onto something you experience.
              </p>
              <aside class="marginalia eureka">
                This is the line that stopped me. I'd spent years on
                the research program and the reading habit and never
                put them in the same room. The agent did it in one
                turn.
              </aside>
            </div>
            <p class="verdict">
              One casual mention, two turns later, the agent has
              connected a childhood reading habit to a research
              program I couldn't start writing. That's the unlock.
              <em>You said something you didn't know you thought.</em>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="prompt" class="prompt-section">
        <p class="kicker">the artifact</p>
        <h2>The prompt</h2>
        <p class="deck">
          Paste it into any fresh conversation with a capable model.
          Answer one question at a time. Push back when it's wrong.
          Ask to be done when you're done.
        </p>

        <div class="prompt-block">
          <button class="copy floating" type="button" data-copy-target="prompt">
            <span class="copy-label">copy</span>
            <span class="copy-done" aria-hidden="true">copied</span>
          </button>
          <pre id="prompt-text"><code>{prompt}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="fence" class="fence">
        <p class="kicker">a fence</p>
        <h2>What this is not</h2>
        <p>
          Not a personality quiz. Not a coaching intake. Not a vibe
          check. Not onboarding for an AI assistant.
        </p>
        <p>
          It's <em>epistemological infrastructure</em> — building the
          shared language and mutual model that lets two minds, one
          biological and one artificial, do better work together than
          either could alone.
        </p>
        <p>
          The eureka isn't "wow, the AI knows me." It's
          <em>"wow, I said something I didn't know I thought, and now
          we have a word for it."</em>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="principles" class="principles">
        <p class="kicker">for the obsessives</p>
        <h2>Why it's built this way</h2>

        <details class="principle">
          <summary>1. Low floor, high ceiling</summary>
          <div>
            <p>
              Every opener is answerable in one breath. The agent's
              follow-up transforms a casual answer into self-discovery.
              You never feel tested; the depth emerges, it isn't
              assigned.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="principle">
          <summary>2. Opt-out is data</summary>
          <div>
            <p>
              Skips, hedges, and "pass" responses are first-class
              signal. They map boundaries, trust thresholds, and
              protected territory. The agent notes them without
              pressure and folds them into the calibration. Chasing a
              skip is a trust violation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="principle">
          <summary>3. Earn the hard questions</summary>
          <div>
            <p>
              Provocative moves — forced tradeoffs, surfacing
              contradictions, kill-your-darlings scenarios — come
              after rapport, not before. And even then they should
              feel like play between colleagues, not interrogation.
              The progression is coffee → sparring → collaboration.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="principle">
          <summary>4. Register evolves</summary>
          <div>
            <p>
              The agent's vocabulary and tone are a live instrument,
              not a fixed setting. It starts warm and accessible,
              mirrors your language as it appears, gradually introduces
              precision as it discovers your conceptual shorthand. By
              the end, the conversation should sound like two people
              deep in the same discipline — because it is.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <p class="credit">
          Built with Claude, sharpened against a near-miss by a
          coworker, refined in a loop until the prompt produced the
          kind of conversation it describes.
        </p>
      </section>

      <Backlinks slug="calibrate" />
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<script>
  // copy-to-clipboard for any button[data-copy-target]
  document.querySelectorAll<HTMLButtonElement>('[data-copy-target]').forEach((btn) => {
    btn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
      const target = document.getElementById('prompt-text');
      if (!target) return;
      const text = target.innerText;
      try {
        await navigator.clipboard.writeText(text);
        btn.classList.add('is-done');
        setTimeout(() => btn.classList.remove('is-done'), 1600);
      } catch {
        const range = document.createRange();
        range.selectNodeContents(target);
        const sel = window.getSelection();
        sel?.removeAllRanges();
        sel?.addRange(range);
      }
    });
  });

  // scroll-synced ToC
  const tocLinks = Array.from(
    document.querySelectorAll<HTMLAnchorElement>('.toc a[data-toc]')
  );
  const sections = tocLinks
    .map((link) => document.querySelector(link.getAttribute('href') || ''))
    .filter((s): s is Element => !!s);

  if ('IntersectionObserver' in window && sections.length) {
    const byId = new Map<string, HTMLAnchorElement>();
    tocLinks.forEach((l) => {
      const id = (l.getAttribute('href') || '').slice(1);
      if (id) byId.set(id, l);
    });

    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
      (entries) => {
        entries.forEach((entry) => {
          const link = byId.get(entry.target.id);
          if (!link) return;
          if (entry.isIntersecting) {
            tocLinks.forEach((l) => l.classList.remove('is-active'));
            link.classList.add('is-active');
          }
        });
      },
      { rootMargin: '-20% 0px -60% 0px', threshold: 0 }
    );
    sections.forEach((s) => observer.observe(s));
  }
</script>

